s roaches’ more nefarious interactions with our species—particularly with those of us living at the margins of society—Schweid also explores their astonishing diversity, how they mate, what they’ll eat, and what we’ve written about them (from Kafka and Nelson Algren to archy and mehitabel). Knowledge soon turns into respect, and Schweid looks beyond his own fears to arrive at an uncomfortable truth: We humans are no more peaceful, tidy, or responsible about taking care of the Earth or each other than these tiny creatures that swarm in the dark corners of our minds, homes, and cereal boxes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCockroachesvAnecdotes. 0aCockroaches-Anecdotes. 0aCockroaches. 0aHuman-animal relationships. 7aNATURE / General.2bisacsh  acockroaches, cockroach, bug, insect, roach, diversity, mating, literary representation, coexistence, morocco, nicaragua, mexico, new york, louisiana, united states of america, usa, franz kafka, realism, fantastic, metamorphosis, allegory, transformation, nelson algren, humor, understanding, relationship, interactions, disliked, extermination, disease.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226260501423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226260501/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles